    "citation": "Sheyer 1994 8046601",
    "population": "N: 22 (USA) Age: 33.7 (20-63) WT: 73.6 (46.4-90)",
    "model_type": "PK",
    "objective": "To model the changing catabolic enzyme activity, linearly related to hepatic microsomal enzyme concentration, along with the serum drug concentration.",
    "covariates": "Concentration, induction, WT",
    "observations": "An atypical one compartment model, using complex methods to take into account the induction and its plateau of CBZ clearance. Of main interest is the finding that autoinduction is maximised above a daily dose of about 500 mg, The unusual type of model doesn’t easily allow the application in practice. The absence of ipred vs obs concentrations doesn’t allow to assess the fit of the model, although the Bayesian predictions do to some extent",
    "dose": "Start of treatment in patients",
    "structure": "1 compartment, linear absorption and elimination with non-linear autoinduction elements",
    "equations": "Kind=theta1 CL0=theta2*WT Cdouble=theta3 Indmax=theta4 Vd=theta5*WT F=theta6 CLt+dt=CLt+dt*Kind*((1+(Ct*Indmax)/(Ct+Cdouble*(Indmax-1)))*CL0-CLt) Ct+dt=Ct+dt*((FD-CLt*Ct)/Vd) F=bioavailability D=dose rate (mg/kg/h) during interval dt Ct=concentration at time t dt=delta time CLt=clearance at time t Kind=induction constant Cdouble=concentration at which induction is maximal CL0=clearance before induction",
    "parameter_values": "theta1=0.00963 theta2=0.021 theta3=7.5 theta4=5 theta5=1.1 theta6=0.9 Variances not reported (“rule of thumb”)",
    "validation": "No / Yes"
  },
